04259nam a22007215i 9780814784679DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20062006nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147846797 a10.18574/nyu/9780814784679.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548448  a(OCoLC)780425945  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF4755b.W36 2008 7aLAW0940002bisacsh1 aWang, Lu-in, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiscrimination by Default :bHow Racism Becomes Routine /cLu-in Wang. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical America ;v900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Discrimination by Default, Discrimination as Default -- t2. Situational Racism -- t3. Self-Fulfilling Stereotypes -- t4. Failures of Imagination -- t5. Discrimination by and as Default in Medical Care -- t6. Overriding the Default -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMuch as we “select” computer settings by default-reflexively, without thinking, and sometimes without realizing there are other options-we often discriminate by default as well. And just as default computer settings tend to become locked in or entrenched as the standard, discrimination by default creates a situation in which disparate outcomes are expected, accepted, and taken for granted. The killing of Amadou Diallo, racial disparities in medical care, the dominance of Whites and men in certain professions, and even the uneven media attention paid to crimes depending on their victims’ race and class, all might be cases of discrimination by, or as, default.Wang contends that, today, most discrimination occurs by default and not design, making legal prohibitions that focus on those who discriminate out of ill will inadequate to redress the largest share of modern discrimination. She draws on social psychology to detail three ways in which unconscious assumptions can lead to discrimination, showing how they play out in a range of everyday settings. Wang then demonstrates how these dynamics interact in medical care to produce an invisible, self-fulfilling, and self-perpetuating prophecy of racial disparity. She goes on to suggest ways in which institutions and individuals might recognize, interrupt, and override the discriminatory default.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEquality before the lawzUnited States. 0aRace discriminationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aLAW / Discrimination.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081479379440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814784679.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814784679423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814784679/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK